Package: shifttx
Title: Targeted Maximum Likelihood Estimation with Stochastic Interventions
Version: 0.0.1
Authors@R: c(
    person("Nima", "Hejazi", email = "nhejazi@berkeley.edu",
           role = c("aut", "cre", "cph")),
    person("David", "Benkeser", email = "benkeser@emory.edu", role = "aut"),
    person("Iván", "Díaz", email = "ild2005@med.cornell.edu", role = "ctb")
  )
Maintainer: Nima Hejazi <nh@nimahejazi.org>
Description: Targeted minimum loss-based estimates of population-level causal
    effects of interventions with stochastically assigned exposures, using a
    causal parameter defined in the context of stochastic treatment regimes,
    including both iterative and one-step variations of the estimator.
    References:
    1. Muñoz, I.D., and van der Laan, M.J. (2012). "Population Intervention
       Causal Effects Based on Stochastic Interventions". Biometrics.
       <doi:10.1111/j.1541-0420.2011.01685.x>
    2. Díaz, I., and van der Laan, M.J. (2017). "Stochastic Treatment Regimes",
       in "Targeted Learning in Data Science: Causal Inference for Complex
       Longitudinal Studies".
Depends: R (>= 3.2.0)
